04773nam a22006615i 9780674028470DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221997mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740284707 a10.4159/97806740284702doi  a(DE-B1597)571772  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aVK221.B65 1997eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a387.508996071 aBolster, W. Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack Jacks :bAfrican American Seamen in the Age of Sail /cW. Jeffrey Bolster. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPREFACE -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tIntroduction: To Tell the Tale -- t1. The Emergence of Black Sailors in Plantation America -- t2. African Roots of Black Seafaring -- t3. The Way of a Ship -- t4. The Boundaries of Race in Maritime Culture -- t5. Possibilities for Freedom -- t6. Precarious Pillar of the Black Community -- t7. Free Sailors and the Struggle with Slavery -- t8. Toward Jim Crow at Sea -- tTables -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew Americans, black or white, recognize the degree to which early African American history is a maritime history. W. Jeffrey Bolster shatters the myth that black seafaring in the age of sail was limited to the Middle Passage. Seafaring was one of the most significant occupations among both enslaved and free black men between 1740 and 1865. Tens of thousands of black seamen sailed on lofty clippers and modest coasters. They sailed in whalers, warships, and privateers. Some were slaves, forced to work at sea, but by 1800 most were free men, seeking liberty and economic opportunity aboard ship. Bolster brings an intimate understanding of the sea to this extraordinary chapter in the formation of black America. Because of their unusual mobility, sailors were the eyes and ears to worlds beyond the limited horizon of black communities ashore. Sometimes helping to smuggle slaves to freedom, they were more often a unique conduit for news and information of concern to blacks. But for all its opportunities, life at sea was difficult. Blacks actively contributed to the Atlantic maritime culture shared by all seamen, but were often outsiders within it. Capturing that tension, Black Jacks examines not only how common experiences drew black and white sailors together—even as deeply internalized prejudices drove them apart—but also how the meaning of race aboard ship changed with time. Bolster traces the story to the end of the Civil War, when emancipated blacks began to be systematically excluded from maritime work. Rescuing African American seamen from obscurity, this stirring account reveals the critical role sailors played in helping forge new identities for black people in America. An epic tale of the rise and fall of black seafaring, Black Jacks is African Americans’ freedom story presented from a fresh perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAfrican American merchant marinersxHistory. 0aSailing shipsxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aSailing shipszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674028470zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674028470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674028470/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL